&lt;p&gt;In April and May 1999, the avant-garde literary journalÂ &lt;em&gt;Writer&lt;/em&gt;Â successively published 13 novelistsâ€™ novels and review articles under the name of â€œpost-avant-gardeâ€ â€” a new concept proposed by the editors ofÂ &lt;em&gt;Writer&lt;/em&gt;. In this research article, this literary journal editing event is studied through Bourdieuâ€™s cultural production field theory from the perspective of contemporary literatureâ€™s production and dissemination system, intending to restore the birth of the â€œpost-avant-gardeâ€ special issue ofÂ &lt;em&gt;Writer&lt;/em&gt;Â through the interrelationship between politics, economy and literature.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the 1990s, the market economy was booming. Policy funds were â€œweanedâ€. Literature lost its sensational effect. In order to survive from the cruel competition, literary journals were forced to begin market-oriented reforms. The contemporary â€œliterary fieldâ€ entered the transitional stage of reforms, and journal editors gained the power to determine whether a new writer can enter the field. Journal editing for commercial interests also became an important means of reform. The concept of â€œpost-avant-gardeâ€ was first put forward by some writers, and later supported by Zong Renfa, editor-in-chief ofÂ &lt;em&gt;Writer&lt;/em&gt;, eventually became a very purposeful journal editing and literary event, showing the compromise of literary authors and editors to the market and business society in this era.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Politics no longer interfered with literature directly. But behind the scenes, it still guided the culture, literary awards and literary atmosphere. The former avant-garde pioneers retreated one after another, and the new writers inherited the lost pioneering spirit, proclaiming the break between them and the history of modern Chinese literature, trying to establish a new space in the nearly completed â€œliterary fieldâ€ for themselves. â€œPost-avant-gardeâ€ became the continuation of the â€œbreakâ€ movement, and it was a manifestation of the fierce collision between the â€œpolitical fieldâ€ and the â€œliterary fieldâ€ in the late 1990s.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;TheÂ &lt;em&gt;Writer&lt;/em&gt;Â journal itself used to have a strong pioneering temperament. However, the editor-in-chief Zong Renfa also had a strong avant-garde literary interest. After he took over the journal, he emphasized that literary journal should be more aware of readersâ€™ reading tastes and cultivate more cutting-edge writers. The â€œpost-avant-gardeâ€ special issue can also be regarded as the result of the inertial sliding of the publicationâ€™s personality.&lt;/p&gt;

